10 Common Exam / Test Tweaks for xv6 Symbolic Links (Task 2)

In practical lab exams for xv6, professors often modify the requirements for the symlink system call and sys_open traversal to test edge cases, security, and performance.

Here are 10 common exam variations for Task 2, complete with the implementation logic for each.

Tweak 1: Strict One-Hop Limit (No Chaining)

The Trap: The professor disables the while loop and explicitly forbids chained symlinks. A symlink can only point to a real file.
Setup: Modify sys_open to use an if statement instead of a while loop, and reject the target if it is also a symlink.

// sys_open() tweak
if(ip->type == T_SYMLINK && !(omode & O_NOFOLLOW)){
    // Read the target path
    readi(ip, 0, (uint64)path, 0, ip->size);
    path[ip->size] = '\0';
    
    iunlockput(ip);
    if((ip = namei(path)) == 0){
        end_op();
        return -1;
    }
    ilock(ip);
    
    // TWEAK: Reject if the target is ALSO a symlink (No chaining)
    if(ip->type == T_SYMLINK){
        iunlockput(ip);
        end_op();
        return -1; 
    }
}


Tweak 2: "Fast Symlinks" (In-Inode Storage)

The Trap: To save disk space, paths shorter than 52 bytes (13 slots * 4 bytes) must be stored directly inside the inode->addrs array instead of allocating a data block with writei().
Setup: Modify both sys_symlink and sys_open.

// sys_symlink() tweak
if(strlen(target) < sizeof(ip->addrs)) {
    // TWEAK: Store string directly in the pointer array! No balloc needed.
    memmove(ip->addrs, target, strlen(target));
    ip->size = strlen(target);
    iupdate(ip);
} else {
    // ... normal writei logic for long paths ...
}

// sys_open() tweak
if(ip->type == T_SYMLINK && !(omode & O_NOFOLLOW)){
    if(ip->size < sizeof(ip->addrs)) {
        // TWEAK: Read directly from the inode's addrs array
        memmove(path, ip->addrs, ip->size);
        path[ip->size] = '\0';
    } else {
        readi(ip, 0, (uint64)path, 0, ip->size);
    }
    // ... namei(path) ...
}


Tweak 3: Strict Same-Directory Symlinks

The Trap: The professor wants to prevent symlinks from pointing outside their current directory to avoid absolute path security risks.
Setup: In sys_symlink, reject any target string that contains a / character.

// sys_symlink() tweak
int i;
for(i = 0; target[i] != '\0'; i++){
    if(target[i] == '/') {
        // TWEAK: Refuse creation if target contains a slash
        end_op();
        return -1; 
    }
}

// Proceed to create inode...
ip = create(path, T_SYMLINK, 0, 0);


Tweak 4: Array-Based Cycle Detection (True Cycles)

The Trap: Instead of a lazy counter (e.g., depth < 10), you must detect actual cycles by tracking the inum of every symlink you visit.
Setup: Create an array in sys_open to track visited inodes.

// sys_open() tweak
uint visited[10];
int depth = 0;

while(ip->type == T_SYMLINK && !(omode & O_NOFOLLOW)){
    // TWEAK: Check if we have seen this exact inode before
    for(int i = 0; i < depth; i++){
        if(visited[i] == ip->inum){
            iunlockput(ip);
            end_op();
            return -1; // Cycle detected!
        }
    }
    
    if(depth >= 10) { iunlockput(ip); end_op(); return -1; }
    
    visited[depth++] = ip->inum; // Add to visited list
    
    readi(ip, 0, (uint64)path, 0, ip->size);
    // ... iunlockput, namei, ilock ...
}


Tweak 5: Opt-In Follow (O_FOLLOW)

The Trap: The default behavior in standard xv6 task is to follow links unless O_NOFOLLOW is passed. The tweak reverses this: open the link itself unless O_FOLLOW is explicitly provided.
Setup: Define O_FOLLOW 0x800 in fcntl.h and invert the check in sys_open.

// sys_open() tweak
// TWEAK: Notice we check IF O_FOLLOW is set, rather than if NOFOLLOW is missing
while(ip->type == T_SYMLINK && (omode & O_FOLLOW)){
    int read_bytes = readi(ip, 0, (uint64)path, 0, ip->size);
    path[read_bytes] = '\0';
    
    iunlockput(ip);
    if((ip = namei(path)) == 0){
        end_op();
        return -1;
    }
    ilock(ip);
    // ...
}


Tweak 6: The readlink System Call

The Trap: The lab requires you to not only follow links, but also implement readlink() to allow user programs to see where a link points.
Setup: Create a brand new system call sys_readlink in sysfile.c.

// New syscall implementation
uint64 sys_readlink(void) {
    char path[MAXPATH];
    uint64 ubuf;
    size_t len;
    struct inode *ip;

    if(argstr(0, path, MAXPATH) < 0 || argaddr(1, &ubuf) < 0 || argint(2, (int*)&len) < 0)
        return -1;

    begin_op();
    if((ip = namei(path)) == 0){ end_op(); return -1; }
    ilock(ip);

    if(ip->type != T_SYMLINK) {
        iunlockput(ip);
        end_op();
        return -1; // Not a symlink!
    }

    int read_len = ip->size < len ? ip->size : len;
    readi(ip, 0, (uint64)path, 0, read_len);
    
    iunlockput(ip);
    end_op();

    if(copyout(myproc()->pagetable, ubuf, path, read_len) < 0)
        return -1;

    return read_len;
}


Tweak 7: No Symlinks to Directories

The Trap: To prevent infinite directory tree loops (which confuse ls and find), the professor forbids opening a symlink if its final destination is a directory.
Setup: Add a check in sys_open after the while loop completes.

// sys_open() tweak
// ... inside sys_open, after the while loop finishes following links ...

if(ip->type == T_DIR && omode != O_RDONLY){
    iunlockput(ip);
    end_op();
    return -1;
}

// TWEAK: Check if the original path was a symlink, and if we landed on a directory
// (Requires a flag 'was_symlink' to be set inside the while loop)
if(was_symlink && ip->type == T_DIR) {
    iunlockput(ip);
    end_op();
    return -1; // Refuse to open symlinks that resolve to directories
}


Tweak 8: Cumulative Path Length Limit

The Trap: A depth of 10 is easily bypassed if each symlink target is huge. You must enforce that the total combined characters read across all traversed links does not exceed MAXPATH (128).
Setup: Track total string length inside the sys_open while loop.

// sys_open() tweak
int total_traversed_chars = 0;

while(ip->type == T_SYMLINK && !(omode & O_NOFOLLOW)){
    total_traversed_chars += ip->size;
    
    // TWEAK: Stop if the total string length exceeds standard MAXPATH
    if(total_traversed_chars > MAXPATH) {
        iunlockput(ip);
        end_op();
        return -1;
    }
    
    readi(ip, 0, (uint64)path, 0, ip->size);
    path[ip->size] = '\0';
    // ...
}


Tweak 9: Custom Error Code for Dangling Links

The Trap: If open() fails, standard xv6 returns -1. The test script might look for a specific -2 return code to differentiate "file doesn't exist" from "dangling symlink".
Setup: Adjust the namei failure block inside the while loop.

// sys_open() tweak
while(ip->type == T_SYMLINK && !(omode & O_NOFOLLOW)){
    readi(ip, 0, (uint64)path, 0, ip->size);
    path[ip->size] = '\0';
    
    iunlockput(ip);
    
    if((ip = namei(path)) == 0){
        end_op();
        // TWEAK: Return -2 specifically for broken/dangling symlinks
        return -2; 
    }
    ilock(ip);
}


Tweak 10: Enforced Single-Block Target Limitation

The Trap: The professor enforces that a symlink string must never span more than one direct block.
Setup: Check the target length against BSIZE inside sys_symlink before doing anything.

// sys_symlink() tweak
// TWEAK: Ensure the path easily fits into a single disk block
if(strlen(target) >= BSIZE) {
    return -1; 
}

begin_op();
ip = create(path, T_SYMLINK, 0, 0);
if(ip == 0){
    end_op();
    return -1;
}

// Safe to writei() knowing it will only consume addrs[0]
if(writei(ip, 0, (uint64)target, 0, strlen(target)) != strlen(target)) {
    // error handling
}
